BU1y0UobrT5_ojWO4=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating dependencies for testing**\\n\\nI realize that to effectively test `copyResources/createContextForSkin`, I need the `maven-artifact` dependency. It seems like the existing version 1.9 might not be adequate due to the default template flag, but 2.0 changes that. It's clear that a proper resource copy requires the skin artifact, so I'll need version 3.6.3 here. For the tests, I'll consider whether to include parser modules, particularly since they might not be necessary if focusing on `copyResources` and `DocumentRenderingContext`. Additionally, I’m contemplating whether to include `plexus-testing` for actual rendering rather than just copying resources.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing render requirements for testing**\\n\\nTo perform a full render with `DefaultSiteRenderer`, I see that I need some injected fields. The TCK can use Sisu/Plexus, but building the container isn't straightforward. Upstream uses `plexus-testing:1.4.0` with `@PlexusTest`, which seems relevant. While generated tests can skip the full render, it looks like meaningful coverage might require rendering. Adding `plexus-testing` as a helper won't complicate the library dependencies too much. However, I have to be cautious about adding too many dependencies, like `maven-artifact` and `doxia-module-apt`, as they could make the native metadata more complex, potentially affecting the native image reflection needs.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dependencies for reachability metadata**\\n\\nMy focus is on obtaining reachability metadata for `doxia-site-renderer`, which means using injection is important, but it could affect metadata generation. It seems extra dependencies may be permitted. The question is asking if I need to set up anything beyond the standard generated test scaffold before achieving meaningful coverage. I'll include `maven-artifact` for a deterministic setup, but I don’t need to restate that. I just have to ensure the guidance is clear when considering full rendering.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"Doxia Site Renderer 2.0.0 is normally used inside Maven/Plexus with Maven's provided artifact classes and parser-module component descriptors; generated tests that exercise real site/skin rendering need those test-time pieces beyond the basic scaffold.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"org.apache.maven:maven-artifact:3.6.3\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"The 2.0.0 renderer exposes skin APIs through org.apache.maven.artifact.Artifact, but the library declares maven-artifact as provided, so it is not pulled transitively for standalone TCK tests.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"org.codehaus.plexus:plexus-testing:1.4.0\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"DefaultSiteRenderer is a Plexus/Sisu component with injected Doxia, parser-module, Velocity, and Plexus fields; upstream 2.0.0 tests use PlexusTest instead of direct construction for meaningful render coverage.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"org.apache.maven.doxia:doxia-module-apt:2.0.0\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"Doxia parser modules are no longer part of doxia-core; the renderer POM notes that modules must be stated so their component descriptors are picked up, and APT is a normal Maven site source format.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"No Docker image or environment variable appears necessary. Update tests for the 2.0.0 API: use DocumentRenderingContext instead of the removed RenderingContext, avoid enableLogging(), setUsingDefaultTemplate(), and SkinResourceLoader, and create a temporary skin JAR when exercising SiteRenderingContext.setSkin()/copyResources(). For full render/locateDocumentFiles coverage, look up SiteRenderer through a Plexus test container rather than calling new DefaultSiteRenderer().\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"The reported javac failure is still primarily an API migration in the existing tests; deterministic setup does not replace updating removed class and method usages.\",\n    \"Parser-module dependency is only needed for tests that render or discover APT site documents; simpler value-object or skin-resource tests may not exercise it.\",\n    \"Local Gradle compile/test/native-image verification remains authoritative for whether these dependencies are sufficient.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_047752afa2162d9f016a3f48d64bac81909d98f3d0bfd08de8\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1061, "output": 1539, "cacheRead": 39424, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 42024, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782532295643, "responseId": "resp_047752afa2162d9f016a3f48c837848190a93b07ea123c0ae7"}, "toolResults": []}
